{"title_page": "Kiwix", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Kiwix\n| logo                   = Kiwix logo v3.svg\n| screenshot             = Kiwix for Android scr1.png\n| caption                = Kiwix on an [[Android (operating system)|Android]]-powered [[tablet computer|tablet]]\n| developer              = Emmanuel Engelhart, Renaud Gaudin\n| released               = <!--{{start date|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| discontinued           = \n| ver layout             = stacked\n| latest release version = {{Multiple releases<!--Ver. 1.0 or later-->\n  |branch1 = Android\n  |version1 = 3.2\n  |date1 = {{start date and age|2020|03|06}}<ref name=sourceforge/>\n  |branch2 = iOS\n  |version2 = 1.11\n  |date2 = {{start date and age|2020|03|20}}<ref>[https://ios.kiwix.org Kiwix iTunes page]</ref>\n  }}\n| latest preview version = {{Multiple releases\n  |branch1 = Desktop\n  |version1 = 2.0\n  |date1 = {{start date and age|2020|02|26}}<ref name=sourceforge/>\n  |branch2 = [[Universal Windows Platform|UWP]]\n  |version2 = 0.9.9.7\n  |date2 = {{start date and age|2018|09|14}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.microsoft.com/store/apps/9P8SLZ4J979J |title=Kiwix JS |work=[[Windows Store]] |publisher=[[Microsoft]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n  }}\n| latest preview date    = \n| operating system       = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[macOS]], [[Windows]], [[Linux]], [[Windows 10 Mobile]]\n| size                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Desktop: {{nowrap|30.6 [[Megabyte|MB]] \u2013 106 MB}}<ref name=sourceforge/>\n* Android: {{nowrap|6.2 MB}}\n* iOS: {{nowrap|48.3 MB}}\n* UWP: {{nowrap|4.2 MB}}\n  }}\n| language count         = 100\n| language footnote      = <ref name=sourceforge/>\n| language               = <!--List them all here-->\n| genre                  = \n| license                = [[GNU General Public License|GPLv3]]\n}}\n'''Kiwix''' is a [[free and open-source]] offline web browser created by [[Emmanuel Engelhart]] and [[Renaud Gaudin]] in 2007.<ref name=\"sutherland2014\" /> It was first launched to allow [[offline]] access to [[Wikipedia]], but has since expanded to include other projects from the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] as well as [[public domain]] texts from [[Project Gutenberg]]. Available in more than 100 languages, Kiwix has been included in several high-profile projects, from smuggling operations in [[North Korea]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/03/north-korea/|title=The plot to free North Korea with smuggled episodes of \"Friends\"|access-date=27 April 2016|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and encyclopedic access in [[Cuba]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ecured.cubava.cu/2017/06/12/como-utilizar-kiwix-como-servidor-local/|title=\u00bfC\u00f3mo utilizar Kiwix como servidor local?|access-date=3 July 2017|language=Spanish|df=dmy-all}}</ref> to [[Google Impact Challenge]]'s recipient [[Biblioth\u00e8ques Sans Fronti\u00e8res]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Les Laur\u00e9ats du Google Impact Challenge|access-date=27 April 2016|url= http://www.tntv.pf/Les-laureats-du-Google-Impact-Challenge_a8169.html|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nFounder [[Emmanuel Engelhart]] sees [[Wikipedia]] as a [[common good]], saying \"The contents of Wikipedia should be available for everyone! Even without [[Internet access]]. This is why I have launched the Kiwix project.\"<ref name=\"sutherland2014\" />\n\nAfter becoming a Wikipedia editor in 2004, Emmanuel Engelhart became interested in developing [[offline]] versions of Wikipedia. A [[Wikipedia:Version 1.0 Editorial Team|project to make a Wikipedia CD]], initiated in 2003, was a trigger for the project.<ref name=\"sutherland2014\">Sutherland, Joe. ''[https://blog.wikimedia.org/2014/09/12/emmanuel-engelhart-inventor-of-kiwix/ Emmanuel Engelhart, Inventor of Kiwix: the Offline Wikipedia Browser]''. In: [[Wikimedia Blog]]. 12 September 2014. Accessed on 26 November 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Kiwix won a grant from [[Wikimedia France]] to build kiwix-plug, which was deployed to [[university|universities]] in eleven countries known as the [[Afripedia Project]].<ref>[http://www.citazine.fr/article/afripedia-wikipedia-pour-afrique-francophone Citazine article on Afripedia (in French)]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.afrik.com/article25968.html|title=Afrip\u00e9dia : un projet de promotion de Wikip\u00e9dia en Afrique|last=Traor\u00e9 |first= Kardiatou|website=www.afrik.com|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In February 2013 Kiwix won [[SourceForge]]'s Project of the Month award<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\">{{cite web|url= http://slashdot.org/topic/cloud/kiwix-aims-to-spread-wikipedias-reach/ |title=Kiwix Aims to spread Wikipedia's Reach |publisher=[[Slashdot]] |date=2013-02-04 |accessdate=2013-07-10 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130302024146/http://slashdot.org/topic/cloud/kiwix-aims-to-spread-wikipedias-reach/ |archivedate=2013-03-02 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and an [[Open Source]] Award in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.netzwoche.ch/News/2015/10/29/OSS-Awards-kueren-die-innovativsten-Schweizer-Open-Source-Projekte.aspx|title=OSS Awards k\u00fcren Schweizer Open-Source-Projekte|publisher=Netzwoche|accessdate =2015-12-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe software is designed as an offline reader for web content. It can be used on computers without an [[internet connection]], computers with a slow or expensive connection, or to avoid [[censorship]]. It can also be used while [[travel]]ing (e.g. on a [[Airplane|plane]] or [[train]]).\n\nUsers first download Kiwix, then download content for offline viewing with Kiwix. [[Data compression|Compression]] saves [[disk space]] and [[bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]]. All of English-language Wikipedia, with pictures, fits on a [[USB stick]] (78&nbsp;GB as of March 2020, or 16&nbsp;GB with no pictures).<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\"/><ref name=\"Content in all languages - Kiwix\">{{Cite web|url= https://wiki.kiwix.org/Content_in_all_languages|title=Content in all languages - Kiwix|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date= 2016-08-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAll content files are compressed in [[ZIM (file format)|ZIM format]], which makes them smaller, but leaves them easy to index, search, and selectively decompress.\n\nThe ZIM files are then opened with Kiwix, which looks and behaves like a [[web browser]]. Kiwix offers full [[text search]], [[tab (GUI)|tabbed navigation]], and the option to export articles to [[PDF]] and [[HTML]].<ref name=sourceforge>{{cite web |url= http://sourceforge.net/projects/kiwix/ |title=Kiwix |publisher=[[SourceForge]] |accessdate=22 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThere is an [[HTTP server]] version called '''kiwix-serve'''; this allows a computer to host Kiwix content, and make it available to other computers on a network.<ref>[https://wiki.kiwix.org/Kiwix-serve Kiwix-serve]</ref> The other computers see an ordinary website. Kiwix-hotspot is an [[HTTP]] server version for [[plug computer]]s,<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\"/> which is often used to provide a [[server (computing)|Wi-Fi server]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.kiwix.org/Kiwix-plug|title=Kiwix-plug - Kiwix|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Available content ==\n[[File:The Goodall girls using Kiwix aboard the Kyrimba.JPG|thumb|left|Reading [[Wikipedia]] through Kiwix on a boat in the [[South Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]].<ref name=\"Sailing the South Pacific\" />]]\n\nA list of content available on Kiwix is available for download, including language-specific sublists.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://wiki.kiwix.org/wiki/Content_in_all_languages|title=Content in all languages - Kiwix |website=wiki.kiwix.org |language=en |access-date=2017-06-09}}</ref> Content can be loaded through Kiwix itself.\n\nSince 2014, most Wikipedia versions are available for download in various different languages.<ref name=\"Content in all languages - Kiwix\"/> For English Wikipedia, a full version containing pictures as well as an alternative version containing text only can be downloaded from the archive. The servers are updated every two to ten months, depending on the size of the file. For English Wikipedia, the update frequency is thus substantially lower than the [[bzip2]] database downloads by the [[Wikimedia Foundation]], which are [[Wikipedia:Database download#English-language Wikipedia|updated twice a month]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Database_download#English-language_Wikipedia|title=Wikipedia Database download: English-language Wikipedia|website=[[Wikipedia]]|accessdate=2017-11-17|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=February 2018}}\n\nBesides Wikipedia, content from the Wikimedia foundation such as [[Wikisource]], [[Wikiquote]], [[Wikivoyage]], [[Wikibooks]], and [[Wikiversity]] are also available for offline viewing in various different languages.<ref>[https://download.kiwix.org/zim/ Zim archive for Kiwix]</ref>\n\nIn November 2014 a ZIM version of all [[public domain|open texts]] forming part of [[Project Gutenberg]] was made available.<ref>[[Emmanuel Engelhart|Engelhart, Emmanuel]]. [https://lists.wikimedia.org/pipermail/wikisource-l/2014-November/002139.html ''50.000 public domain books available to everybody, everywhere, offline''.] [[Wikisource]]-l-Mailinglist, [[Wikimedia Foundation]]. 19 November 2014. Accessed on 26 November 2014.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://ultimategerardm.blogspot.ch/2014/11/wikimedia-project-gutenberg-sum-of-all.html|title=Words and what not: #Wikimedia & Project #Gutenberg - the sum of all knowledge|website= ultimategerardm.blogspot.ch|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBesides [[public domain]] content, works licensed under a [[Creative Commons]] [[Creative Commons license|license]] are available for download as well. For example, offline versions of the [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] [[wiki]] containing user documentation for the Ubuntu operating system,<ref>''[http://wiki.ubuntuusers.de/Wiki/Hilfsmittel#Kiwix Ubuntuusers Hilfsmittel]''</ref> ZIM editions of [[TED (conference)|TED conference]] talks<ref>[https://download.kiwix.org/zim/ted/ Kiwix archive for TED]</ref> and videos from [[Crash Course (YouTube)|Crash Course]] are available in the Kiwix archive as ZIM file formats.<ref>[https://download.kiwix.org/zim/other/ Kiwix archive for additional content]</ref>\n\n== Deployments ==\nKiwix can be installed on a [[desktop computer]] as a stand-alone program, installed on a [[tablet computer|tablet]] or [[smartphone]], or can create its own [[WLAN]] environment from a [[Raspberry pi]].\n\nAs a software development project, Kiwix itself is not directly involved in deployment projects. However, third party organisations do use the software as a component of their own projects. Examples include:\n[[File:Carte localisation Afrip\u00e9dia hors-ligne.png|thumb|Locations of 13 universities in 11 countries where Kiwix was deployed as part of the [[Afripedia Project]].]]\n* Universities and [[library|libraries]] that can't afford [[broadband]] Internet access.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url= https://wiki.kiwix.org/Special:MyLanguage/Main_Page|title=Main Page - Kiwix|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** The Afripedia Project set up kiwix servers in French-speaking universities, some of them with no Internet access, in 11 [[African countries]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2013/01/24/afripedia-project-increasing-off-line-access-to-wikipedia-in-africa/|title=Afripedia project increasing off-line access to Wikipedia in Africa|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]] |access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[School]]s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asri-education.org/asriedu-logitheque-kiwix |title=(fr) ASRI Education may 2013 |language=fr |publisher=Asri-education.org |date= |accessdate=2013-07-10 |df=dmy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720065256/http://asri-education.org/asriedu-logitheque-kiwix |archive-date=2014-07-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in [[developing countries]], where access to the internet is difficult or too expensive.<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" />\n** Installed on [[computer]]s used for the [[One Laptop per Child]] project.<ref name=\"sutherland2014\" />\n** Installed on [[Raspberry Pi]]s for use in schools with no easy access to [[electricity]] in [[Tanzania]]<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://blog.wikimedia.org/2015/03/17/raspberry-pi-tanzania-school/|title=Raspberry Pi in Masekelo: Bringing Wikipedia to a school without electricity|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> by the Tanzania Development Trust.\n** Installed on [[tablet computer|tablets]] in schools in [[Mali]] as part of the MALebooks project.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://blog.wikimedia.org/2015/05/14/e-readers-in-mali/|title=Children in Mali can now read Wikipedia offline, thanks to MALebooks e-readers|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Used by [[school teacher]]s and [[university professor]]s, as well as [[student]]s, in [[Senegal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://outreach.wikimedia.org/wiki/Education/Newsletter/September_2016/West_African_schools_will_test_Kiwix,_the_offline_Wikipedia_reader|title=West African schools will test Kiwix, the offline Wikipedia reader|work=Wikimedia Outreach Education Newsletter|publisher=[[Wikimedia Foundation]]|date=2016-08-31|access-date=2017-06-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Deployed in [[Benin]] during [[teacher training]] [[seminar]]s run by Zedaga,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zedaga.ch/nos-partenaires/soutiens-individuels/|title=Kiwix is mentioned on the thank-you page|website=Zedaga|language=French|access-date=2017-06-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref> a Swiss [[NGO]] specialized in education.\n** The ''[[Orange S.A.|Fondation Orange]]'' has used kiwix-serve in its own [[French language]] technological knowledge product they have deployed in [[Africa]].<ref>[http://www.fondationorange.com/le-programme-ecoles-numeriques Fondation Orange: le programme \"\u00e9coles num\u00e9riques\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405200750/http://www.fondationorange.com/le-programme-ecoles-numeriques |date=5 April 2015}}.</ref>\n** A [[SOS Children's Villages UK#Wikipedia for Schools|special version]] for the organisation [[SOS Children's Villages]] was developed, initially for developing countries, but it is also used in the developed world.\n* [[At sea]] and in other remote areas:<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" /><ref name=\"Sailing the South Pacific\">{{Cite web|url= https://blog.wikimedia.org/2014/11/14/sailing-south-pacific-with-wikipedia-on-board-goodall-family/|title=Sailing the South Pacific with a copy of Wikipedia on board: The Goodall Family|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Aboard [[ship]]s in [[Antarctic]] waters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2014/10/10/hans-oleander-offline-wikipedia-guide-tours-bottom-earth/|title=Hans Oleander: Using offline Wikipedia to guide tours at the bottom of the Earth|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2017-06-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** By the [[Senegalese Navy]] in their [[patrol ship]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gazetekarinca.com/2017/05/kiwixle-wikipediaya-ulasmak-hala-mumkun/|title=Kiwix\u2019le Wikipedia\u2019ya ula\u015fmak hala m\u00fcmk\u00fcn|website=gazetekarinca.com|date=2017-05-05|access-date=2016-03-08|language=tr|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Included in Navigatrix, a [[Linux distribution]] for people on [[boat]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://navigatrix.net/viewtopic.php?f=3&t=639|title=Navigatrix.net - A Voyager's Companion|website=navigatrix.net|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yourcruisingeditor.wordpress.com/2010/07/30/navigatrix-the-first-linux-distribution-for-cruisers/|title=Navigatrix \u2013 the first Linux distribution for cruisers|website=Your Cruising Editor|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* On a train or plane.<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://a3nm.net/blog/kiwix.html|title=A local copy of Wikipedia with Kiwix - a3nm's blog|last=Amarilli|first=Antoine|website=a3nm.net|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* In European and US [[prison education]] programs.<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" />\n\n===Package managers and app stores===\n[[File:Kiwix page view.jpg|thumb|[[Medical Wikipedia]] app on a [[smartphone]].]]\nKiwix was formerly available in the native [[package manager]]s of some [[Linux]] distributions. However, Kiwix is currently not available in most package databases, due to XULRunner, a program on which Kiwix depends, being [[deprecate]]d by [[Mozilla]] and removed from the [[package database]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.kiwix.org/wiki/Debian|title=Debian|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date=2020-01-06|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Kiwix is available in the [[Sugar (software)|Sugar]] and [[ArchLinux]] Linux distributions. It is also available on [[Android (operating system)|Android]].\n\nKiwix is available in the [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Microsoft Store]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/store/apps/9P8SLZ4J979J|title=Get Kiwix JS - Microsoft Store|website=[[Microsoft Store Online]]|access-date=2018-02-12|df=dmy-all}}</ref> on [[Google Play]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.kiwix.kiwixmobile|title=Kiwix, Wikipedia offline - Android Apps on Google Play|website=[[Google Play]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iOS]] [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/kiwix/id997079563?mt=8|title=Kiwix on the App Store|website=[[App Store (iOS)|App Store]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 2015, a series of \"customized apps\" have also been released, of which [[Medical Wikipedia]] and [[PhET]] simulations are the two largest.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Internet-in-a-Box]]\n* [[XOWA]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|https://kiwix.org/}}\n* {{SourceForge|kiwix}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uw9nHXSWZTo Explanation of Kiwix from [[Wikimania 2013]]]\n* [https://blog.wikimedia.org/tag/kiwix/ Kiwix stories on the Wikimedia Blog]\n{{Wikipedia}}\n\n[[Category:Wikipedia]]\n[[Category:Cross-platform software]]\n[[Category:Free software]]\n[[Category:Free and open-source Android software]]\n[[Category:Free educational software]]\n[[Category:Free web server software]]\n[[Category:Free mobile software]]\n[[Category:Software using the GPL license]]\n[[Category:2010 software]]\n[[Category:Software development]]\n[[Category:Travel gear]]\n[[Category:Internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Internet censorship]]\n[[Category:Book censorship]]\n[[Category:E-book suppliers]]\n[[Category:Publishing]]\n[[Category:Software that uses XUL]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Kiwix\n| logo                   = Kiwix logo v3.png\n| screenshot             = Kiwix for Android scr1.png\n| caption                = Kiwix on an [[Android (operating system)|Android]]-powered [[tablet computer|tablet]]\n| developer              = Emmanuel Engelhart, Renaud Gaudin\n| released               = <!--{{start date|YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| discontinued           = \n| ver layout             = stacked\n| latest release version = {{Multiple releases<!--Ver. 1.0 or later-->\n  |branch1 = Android\n  |version1 = 3.2\n  |date1 = {{start date and age|2020|03|06}}<ref name=sourceforge/>\n  |branch2 = iOS\n  |version2 = 1.11\n  |date2 = {{start date and age|2020|03|20}}<ref>[https://ios.kiwix.org Kiwix iTunes page]</ref>\n  }}\n| latest preview version = {{Multiple releases\n  |branch1 = Desktop\n  |version1 = 2.0\n  |date1 = {{start date and age|2020|02|26}}<ref name=sourceforge/>\n  |branch2 = [[Universal Windows Platform|UWP]]\n  |version2 = 0.9.9.7\n  |date2 = {{start date and age|2018|09|14}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.microsoft.com/store/apps/9P8SLZ4J979J |title=Kiwix JS |work=[[Windows Store]] |publisher=[[Microsoft]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n  }}\n| latest preview date    = \n| operating system       = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[macOS]], [[Windows]], [[Linux]], [[Windows 10 Mobile]]\n| size                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Desktop: {{nowrap|30.6 [[Megabyte|MB]] \u2013 106 MB}}<ref name=sourceforge/>\n* Android: {{nowrap|6.2 MB}}\n* iOS: {{nowrap|48.3 MB}}\n* UWP: {{nowrap|4.2 MB}}\n  }}\n| language count         = 100\n| language footnote      = <ref name=sourceforge/>\n| language               = <!--List them all here-->\n| genre                  = \n| license                = [[GNU General Public License|GPLv3]]\n}}\n'''Kiwix''' is a [[free and open-source]] offline web browser created by [[Emmanuel Engelhart]] and [[Renaud Gaudin]] in 2007.<ref name=\"sutherland2014\" /> It was first launched to allow [[offline]] access to [[Wikipedia]], but has since expanded to include other projects from the [[Wikimedia Foundation]] as well as [[public domain]] texts from [[Project Gutenberg]]. Available in more than 100 languages, Kiwix has been included in several high-profile projects, from smuggling operations in [[North Korea]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/03/north-korea/|title=The plot to free North Korea with smuggled episodes of \"Friends\"|access-date=27 April 2016|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and encyclopedic access in [[Cuba]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ecured.cubava.cu/2017/06/12/como-utilizar-kiwix-como-servidor-local/|title=\u00bfC\u00f3mo utilizar Kiwix como servidor local?|access-date=3 July 2017|language=Spanish|df=dmy-all}}</ref> to [[Google Impact Challenge]]'s recipient [[Biblioth\u00e8ques Sans Fronti\u00e8res]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Les Laur\u00e9ats du Google Impact Challenge|access-date=27 April 2016|url= http://www.tntv.pf/Les-laureats-du-Google-Impact-Challenge_a8169.html|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nFounder [[Emmanuel Engelhart]] sees [[Wikipedia]] as a [[common good]], saying \"The contents of Wikipedia should be available for everyone! Even without [[Internet access]]. This is why I have launched the Kiwix project.\"<ref name=\"sutherland2014\" />\n\nAfter becoming a Wikipedia editor in 2004, Emmanuel Engelhart became interested in developing [[offline]] versions of Wikipedia. A [[Wikipedia:Version 1.0 Editorial Team|project to make a Wikipedia CD]], initiated in 2003, was a trigger for the project.<ref name=\"sutherland2014\">Sutherland, Joe. ''[https://blog.wikimedia.org/2014/09/12/emmanuel-engelhart-inventor-of-kiwix/ Emmanuel Engelhart, Inventor of Kiwix: the Offline Wikipedia Browser]''. In: [[Wikimedia Blog]]. 12 September 2014. Accessed on 26 November 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Kiwix won a grant from [[Wikimedia France]] to build kiwix-plug, which was deployed to [[university|universities]] in eleven countries known as the [[Afripedia Project]].<ref>[http://www.citazine.fr/article/afripedia-wikipedia-pour-afrique-francophone Citazine article on Afripedia (in French)]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.afrik.com/article25968.html|title=Afrip\u00e9dia : un projet de promotion de Wikip\u00e9dia en Afrique|last=Traor\u00e9 |first= Kardiatou|website=www.afrik.com|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In February 2013 Kiwix won [[SourceForge]]'s Project of the Month award<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\">{{cite web|url= http://slashdot.org/topic/cloud/kiwix-aims-to-spread-wikipedias-reach/ |title=Kiwix Aims to spread Wikipedia's Reach |publisher=[[Slashdot]] |date=2013-02-04 |accessdate=2013-07-10 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130302024146/http://slashdot.org/topic/cloud/kiwix-aims-to-spread-wikipedias-reach/ |archivedate=2013-03-02 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and an [[Open Source]] Award in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.netzwoche.ch/News/2015/10/29/OSS-Awards-kueren-die-innovativsten-Schweizer-Open-Source-Projekte.aspx|title=OSS Awards k\u00fcren Schweizer Open-Source-Projekte|publisher=Netzwoche|accessdate =2015-12-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe software is designed as an offline reader for web content. It can be used on computers without an [[internet connection]], computers with a slow or expensive connection, or to avoid [[censorship]]. It can also be used while [[travel]]ing (e.g. on a [[Airplane|plane]] or [[train]]).\n\nUsers first download Kiwix, then download content for offline viewing with Kiwix. [[Data compression|Compression]] saves [[disk space]] and [[bandwidth (computing)|bandwidth]]. All of English-language Wikipedia, with pictures, fits on a [[USB stick]] (78&nbsp;GB as of March 2020, or 16&nbsp;GB with no pictures).<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\"/><ref name=\"Content in all languages - Kiwix\">{{Cite web|url= https://wiki.kiwix.org/Content_in_all_languages|title=Content in all languages - Kiwix|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date= 2016-08-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAll content files are compressed in [[ZIM (file format)|ZIM format]], which makes them smaller, but leaves them easy to index, search, and selectively decompress.\n\nThe ZIM files are then opened with Kiwix, which looks and behaves like a [[web browser]]. Kiwix offers full [[text search]], [[tab (GUI)|tabbed navigation]], and the option to export articles to [[PDF]] and [[HTML]].<ref name=sourceforge>{{cite web |url= http://sourceforge.net/projects/kiwix/ |title=Kiwix |publisher=[[SourceForge]] |accessdate=22 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThere is an [[HTTP server]] version called '''kiwix-serve'''; this allows a computer to host Kiwix content, and make it available to other computers on a network.<ref>[https://wiki.kiwix.org/Kiwix-serve Kiwix-serve]</ref> The other computers see an ordinary website. Kiwix-hotspot is an [[HTTP]] server version for [[plug computer]]s,<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\"/> which is often used to provide a [[server (computing)|Wi-Fi server]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.kiwix.org/Kiwix-plug|title=Kiwix-plug - Kiwix|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Available content ==\n[[File:The Goodall girls using Kiwix aboard the Kyrimba.JPG|thumb|left|Reading [[Wikipedia]] through Kiwix on a boat in the [[South Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]].<ref name=\"Sailing the South Pacific\" />]]\n\nA list of content available on Kiwix is available for download, including language-specific sublists.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://wiki.kiwix.org/wiki/Content_in_all_languages|title=Content in all languages - Kiwix |website=wiki.kiwix.org |language=en |access-date=2017-06-09}}</ref> Content can be loaded through Kiwix itself.\n\nSince 2014, most Wikipedia versions are available for download in various different languages.<ref name=\"Content in all languages - Kiwix\"/> For English Wikipedia, a full version containing pictures as well as an alternative version containing text only can be downloaded from the archive. The servers are updated every two to ten months, depending on the size of the file. For English Wikipedia, the update frequency is thus substantially lower than the [[bzip2]] database downloads by the [[Wikimedia Foundation]], which are [[Wikipedia:Database download#English-language Wikipedia|updated twice a month]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Database_download#English-language_Wikipedia|title=Wikipedia Database download: English-language Wikipedia|website=[[Wikipedia]]|accessdate=2017-11-17|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=February 2018}}\n\nBesides Wikipedia, content from the Wikimedia foundation such as [[Wikisource]], [[Wikiquote]], [[Wikivoyage]], [[Wikibooks]], and [[Wikiversity]] are also available for offline viewing in various different languages.<ref>[https://download.kiwix.org/zim/ Zim archive for Kiwix]</ref>\n\nIn November 2014 a ZIM version of all [[public domain|open texts]] forming part of [[Project Gutenberg]] was made available.<ref>[[Emmanuel Engelhart|Engelhart, Emmanuel]]. [https://lists.wikimedia.org/pipermail/wikisource-l/2014-November/002139.html ''50.000 public domain books available to everybody, everywhere, offline''.] [[Wikisource]]-l-Mailinglist, [[Wikimedia Foundation]]. 19 November 2014. Accessed on 26 November 2014.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://ultimategerardm.blogspot.ch/2014/11/wikimedia-project-gutenberg-sum-of-all.html|title=Words and what not: #Wikimedia & Project #Gutenberg - the sum of all knowledge|website= ultimategerardm.blogspot.ch|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBesides [[public domain]] content, works licensed under a [[Creative Commons]] [[Creative Commons license|license]] are available for download as well. For example, offline versions of the [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] [[wiki]] containing user documentation for the Ubuntu operating system,<ref>''[http://wiki.ubuntuusers.de/Wiki/Hilfsmittel#Kiwix Ubuntuusers Hilfsmittel]''</ref> ZIM editions of [[TED (conference)|TED conference]] talks<ref>[https://download.kiwix.org/zim/ted/ Kiwix archive for TED]</ref> and videos from [[Crash Course (YouTube)|Crash Course]] are available in the Kiwix archive as ZIM file formats.<ref>[https://download.kiwix.org/zim/other/ Kiwix archive for additional content]</ref>\n\n== Deployments ==\nKiwix can be installed on a [[desktop computer]] as a stand-alone program, installed on a [[tablet computer|tablet]] or [[smartphone]], or can create its own [[WLAN]] environment from a [[Raspberry pi]].\n\nAs a software development project, Kiwix itself is not directly involved in deployment projects. However, third party organisations do use the software as a component of their own projects. Examples include:\n[[File:Carte localisation Afrip\u00e9dia hors-ligne.png|thumb|Locations of 13 universities in 11 countries where Kiwix was deployed as part of the [[Afripedia Project]].]]\n* Universities and [[library|libraries]] that can't afford [[broadband]] Internet access.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url= https://wiki.kiwix.org/Special:MyLanguage/Main_Page|title=Main Page - Kiwix|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** The Afripedia Project set up kiwix servers in French-speaking universities, some of them with no Internet access, in 11 [[African countries]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2013/01/24/afripedia-project-increasing-off-line-access-to-wikipedia-in-africa/|title=Afripedia project increasing off-line access to Wikipedia in Africa|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]] |access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[School]]s<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asri-education.org/asriedu-logitheque-kiwix |title=(fr) ASRI Education may 2013 |language=fr |publisher=Asri-education.org |date= |accessdate=2013-07-10 |df=dmy-all |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720065256/http://asri-education.org/asriedu-logitheque-kiwix |archive-date=2014-07-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in [[developing countries]], where access to the internet is difficult or too expensive.<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" />\n** Installed on [[computer]]s used for the [[One Laptop per Child]] project.<ref name=\"sutherland2014\" />\n** Installed on [[Raspberry Pi]]s for use in schools with no easy access to [[electricity]] in [[Tanzania]]<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://blog.wikimedia.org/2015/03/17/raspberry-pi-tanzania-school/|title=Raspberry Pi in Masekelo: Bringing Wikipedia to a school without electricity|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> by the Tanzania Development Trust.\n** Installed on [[tablet computer|tablets]] in schools in [[Mali]] as part of the MALebooks project.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://blog.wikimedia.org/2015/05/14/e-readers-in-mali/|title=Children in Mali can now read Wikipedia offline, thanks to MALebooks e-readers|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Used by [[school teacher]]s and [[university professor]]s, as well as [[student]]s, in [[Senegal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://outreach.wikimedia.org/wiki/Education/Newsletter/September_2016/West_African_schools_will_test_Kiwix,_the_offline_Wikipedia_reader|title=West African schools will test Kiwix, the offline Wikipedia reader|work=Wikimedia Outreach Education Newsletter|publisher=[[Wikimedia Foundation]]|date=2016-08-31|access-date=2017-06-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Deployed in [[Benin]] during [[teacher training]] [[seminar]]s run by Zedaga,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zedaga.ch/nos-partenaires/soutiens-individuels/|title=Kiwix is mentioned on the thank-you page|website=Zedaga|language=French|access-date=2017-06-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref> a Swiss [[NGO]] specialized in education.\n** The ''[[Orange S.A.|Fondation Orange]]'' has used kiwix-serve in its own [[French language]] technological knowledge product they have deployed in [[Africa]].<ref>[http://www.fondationorange.com/le-programme-ecoles-numeriques Fondation Orange: le programme \"\u00e9coles num\u00e9riques\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405200750/http://www.fondationorange.com/le-programme-ecoles-numeriques |date=5 April 2015}}.</ref>\n** A [[SOS Children's Villages UK#Wikipedia for Schools|special version]] for the organisation [[SOS Children's Villages]] was developed, initially for developing countries, but it is also used in the developed world.\n* [[At sea]] and in other remote areas:<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" /><ref name=\"Sailing the South Pacific\">{{Cite web|url= https://blog.wikimedia.org/2014/11/14/sailing-south-pacific-with-wikipedia-on-board-goodall-family/|title=Sailing the South Pacific with a copy of Wikipedia on board: The Goodall Family|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Aboard [[ship]]s in [[Antarctic]] waters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2014/10/10/hans-oleander-offline-wikipedia-guide-tours-bottom-earth/|title=Hans Oleander: Using offline Wikipedia to guide tours at the bottom of the Earth|website=[[Wikimedia Blog]]|access-date=2017-06-11|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** By the [[Senegalese Navy]] in their [[patrol ship]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gazetekarinca.com/2017/05/kiwixle-wikipediaya-ulasmak-hala-mumkun/|title=Kiwix\u2019le Wikipedia\u2019ya ula\u015fmak hala m\u00fcmk\u00fcn|website=gazetekarinca.com|date=2017-05-05|access-date=2016-03-08|language=tr|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n** Included in Navigatrix, a [[Linux distribution]] for people on [[boat]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://navigatrix.net/viewtopic.php?f=3&t=639|title=Navigatrix.net - A Voyager's Companion|website=navigatrix.net|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yourcruisingeditor.wordpress.com/2010/07/30/navigatrix-the-first-linux-distribution-for-cruisers/|title=Navigatrix \u2013 the first Linux distribution for cruisers|website=Your Cruising Editor|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* On a train or plane.<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://a3nm.net/blog/kiwix.html|title=A local copy of Wikipedia with Kiwix - a3nm's blog|last=Amarilli|first=Antoine|website=a3nm.net|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* In European and US [[prison education]] programs.<ref name=\"Slashdot.org\" />\n\n===Package managers and app stores===\n[[File:Kiwix page view.jpg|thumb|[[Medical Wikipedia]] app on a [[smartphone]].]]\nKiwix was formerly available in the native [[package manager]]s of some [[Linux]] distributions. However, Kiwix is currently not available in most package databases, due to XULRunner, a program on which Kiwix depends, being [[deprecate]]d by [[Mozilla]] and removed from the [[package database]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.kiwix.org/wiki/Debian|title=Debian|website=wiki.kiwix.org|access-date=2020-01-06|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Kiwix is available in the [[Sugar (software)|Sugar]] and [[ArchLinux]] Linux distributions. It is also available on [[Android (operating system)|Android]].\n\nKiwix is available in the [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Microsoft Store]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.microsoft.com/store/apps/9P8SLZ4J979J|title=Get Kiwix JS - Microsoft Store|website=[[Microsoft Store Online]]|access-date=2018-02-12|df=dmy-all}}</ref> on [[Google Play]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.kiwix.kiwixmobile|title=Kiwix, Wikipedia offline - Android Apps on Google Play|website=[[Google Play]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]]'s [[iOS]] [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/kiwix/id997079563?mt=8|title=Kiwix on the App Store|website=[[App Store (iOS)|App Store]]|access-date=2016-03-08|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 2015, a series of \"customized apps\" have also been released, of which [[Medical Wikipedia]] and [[PhET]] simulations are the two largest.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Internet-in-a-Box]]\n* [[XOWA]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|https://kiwix.org/}}\n* {{SourceForge|kiwix}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uw9nHXSWZTo Explanation of Kiwix from [[Wikimania 2013]]]\n* [https://blog.wikimedia.org/tag/kiwix/ Kiwix stories on the Wikimedia Blog]\n{{Wikipedia}}\n\n[[Category:Wikipedia]]\n[[Category:Cross-platform software]]\n[[Category:Free software]]\n[[Category:Free and open-source Android software]]\n[[Category:Free educational software]]\n[[Category:Free web server software]]\n[[Category:Free mobile software]]\n[[Category:Software using the GPL license]]\n[[Category:2010 software]]\n[[Category:Software development]]\n[[Category:Travel gear]]\n[[Category:Internet privacy]]\n[[Category:Internet censorship]]\n[[Category:Book censorship]]\n[[Category:E-book suppliers]]\n[[Category:Publishing]]\n[[Category:Software that uses XUL]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "The other Kiwix guy", "label": "safe", "comment": "png -> svg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiwix"}
{"title_page": "Cirith Ungol (band)", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Cirith Ungol\n| image               =\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Ventura, California]], [[United States]]\n| genre               = {{unbulleted list|[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]|[[doom metal]]|[[power metal]]|[[hard rock]] (early)}}\n| years_active        = 1971\u20131992, 2016\u2013present\n| label               = [[Metal Blade Records|Metal Blade]], Liquid Flames, [[Restless Records|Restless]]\n| associated_acts     = [[#Titanic|Titanic]]<br>[[Falcon (band)|Falcon]]<br>[[Angry Samoans]]\n| website             = http://www.truemetal.org/cirithungol/\n| current_members     = Tim Baker<br>Greg Lindstrom<br>Robert Garven<br>Jim Barraza\n| past_members        = Neal Beattie<br>Jerry Fogle<br>Michael Vujea<br>Bob Warrenburg<br>Vernon Green\n}}\n\n'''Cirith Ungol''' is an American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band formed in late 1971 in [[Ventura, California|Ventura]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vcstar.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/09/24/venturas-cirith-ungol-plays-music-fans-who-like-their-metal-heavy/1410401002/|title= Ventura's Cirith Ungol plays for music fans who like their metal heavy|first=Bill |last=Locey|newspaper=[[Ventura County Star]]|date= September 24, 2018|access-date=28 September 2018|url-status=live|archive-date=2018-09-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926204124/https://www.vcstar.com/story/entertainment/music/2018/09/24/venturas-cirith-ungol-plays-music-fans-who-like-their-metal-heavy/1410401002/?from=new-cookie}}</ref> The group is known for lyrics based on [[fantasy fiction|fantasy]] (particularly [[sword and sorcery]]) and is an early [[doom metal|doom]] and [[power metal]] band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=84308 |website=Metalunderground.com|title=Cirith Ungol}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1970s, the band generally played a style of heavy metal heavily rooted in [[Hard rock|hard]] and [[progressive rock]]. The band's first studio album, ''[[Frost and Fire (album)|Frost and Fire]]'' (1981), featured a heavier sound,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/60087/Cirith-Ungol-Frost-and-Fire/ |website=Sputnikmusic.com|title=Frost and Fire}}</ref> generally regarded as an early example of [[Power metal#American style|American power metal]]. By the band's second studio album, ''[[King of the Dead (album)|King of the Dead]]'' (1984), the band had solidified their power metal style of playing while gravitating toward a much 'darker' sound, with many considering the album among the [[Doom metal#Development (1980s)|first]] [[doom metal]] releases.\n\n==History==\n===Titanic===\nGreg Lindstrom, Robert Garven, Jerry Fogle and Pat Galligan (later a guitarist in [[Angry Samoans]]) played in Titanic, their first band in junior high school. With a desire to play heavier music similar to that of [[Mountain (band)|Mountain]] and [[Grand Funk Railroad]], the rest of the band parted with Galligan and founded Cirith Ungol in late 1971.\n\n===Early history===\nAfter forming in late 1971, the band played their first gig on January 1, 1972 at an anti-Vietnam war peace rally.\n\nIn 1980, they were signed by Liquid Flames Records, and released their first album, ''[[Frost and Fire (album)|Frost and Fire]]'', with Tim Baker on vocals and songs written by bassist and guitarist Greg Lindstrom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Cirith-Ungol-Frost-And-Fire/release/1332428 |website=Discogs.com|title=Frost and Fire}}</ref> Their second album, ''[[King of the Dead (album)|King of the Dead]]'' was released in on July 2, 1984 and contained lyrics primarily written by vocalist Tim Baker and drummer Robert Garven.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darklyrics.com/c/cirithungol.html |website=Darklyrics.com|title=Cirith Ungol}}</ref> The album was then followed by ''[[One Foot in Hell]]'' on August 12, 1986, and ''[[Paradise Lost (Cirith Ungol album)|Paradise Lost]]'' on August 23, 1991.\n\n===Disbandment===\nThey played their last live show on December 13, 1991 and disbanded in 1992, following frustration with their record label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truemetal.org/cirithungol/page.php?page_id=150 |website=Truemetal.org|title=Cirith Ungol Comeback}}</ref>\n\n===1992\u20132016===\nIn 2001, [[Metal Blade Records]] released in Germany ''Servants of Chaos'', a compilation album of unreleased demos and live songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalhead.it/?p=2692 |website=Metalhead.it|title=Cirith Ungol}}</ref> With old tapes and assistance from Lindstrom and Garven, it was an attempt to give fans a wealth of archival and previously unheard material before the tapes deteriorated beyond retrieval. This double-CD was later re-released worldwide, with a rare 1984 live DVD recorded at [[Reseda Country Club|Wolf & Rissmiller's Country Club]] in California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truemetal.org/cirithungol/page.php?page_id=157 |website=Truemetal.org|title=Cirith Ungol}}</ref>\n\nLindstrom now plays with Falcon, who perform some Cirith Ungol songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.falconband.net/falconbio.htm|title=Falcon Bio|website=Falconband.net|accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nFounding guitarist Jerry Fogle died from liver failure on August 20, 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metal-archives.com/artists/Jerry_Fogle/10836 |website=Metal-archives.com|title=Jerry Fogle}}</ref>\n\n===Reunion===\nThe band was reformed by members Tim Baker, Robert Garven, Jim Barraza, and Greg Lindstrom on October 8, 2016 at the 2nd annual [[Frost and Fire Festival]] in [[Ventura, California]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nightdemon.net/frost-and-fire |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151101145418/http://nightdemon.net/frost-and-fire |archive-date=2015-11-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Throughout 2017, the band had set out to headline and co-headline several European and US festivals, including Keep It True (Germany), Up The Hammers (Greece), Defenders Of The Old (US), Chaos Descends (Germany), Psycho Las Vegas (US), Days Of Darkness (US) and Hammer of Doom (Germany).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/cirithungolofficial/|title=Cirith Ungol|website=Facebook.com|accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, Cirith Ungol performed at the Hell's Heroes Festival in Houston, Texas and at the NYDM Spring Bash in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. In August 2018, Cirith Ungol released the single \"Witch's Game\".\n\n==Name==\nThe band took their name from the mountain pass [[Cirith Ungol]] in [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]'s epic fantasy novel ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vcstar.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/10/07/cirith-ungol-grows-fan-base-without-really-trying/91573612/|title=Cirith Ungol grows fan base without really trying|first=Bill |last=Locey|newspaper=[[Ventura County Star]]|date=October 7, 2016|access-date=7 October 2018}}</ref>  The name is [[Sindarin|Elvish]] and means \"Pass of the Spider.\" While the place in Tolkien's book is pronounced \"kirith ungol,\" the band pronounced it \"sirith ungol.\" The band said they had some problems with the name:\n\n{{quotation|Everyone in the band was a big \"Sword and Sorcery\" literature fan, especially Greg [Lindstrom, guitars] and I. He would always turn us on to the great writers who gave us inspiration for our music. We read all the books... [[Conan The Barbarian|Conan]], [[Bran Mak Morn]], etcetera, but the books that stood out in my mind are [[Michael Moorcock]]'s masterpieces: [[Elric]], [[Hawkmoon]], [[Corum Jhaelen Irsei|Corum]] among others. Greg Lindstrom and I met at an English Literature class where the teacher was reading Lord of the Rings... and Greg and I read it and it had an influence on our music and feelings. In retrospect I wish we had picked something easier to remember because a lot of our trouble has been over our name. People couldn't pronounce it or remember it, but we figured once they did they wouldn't forget it! We've humorously been called \"Sarah's Uncle\" and \"Serious Uncool,\" for example! I know other bands are using the Tolkien angle. Led Zeppelin even made references to it in their earlier songs. I think he was an influence both then and now on many people.|Robert Garven<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050223140041/http://www.geocities.com/metalnightmarezine/cirithungol.html|url=http://www.geocities.com/metalnightmarezine/cirithungol.html |archivedate=February 23, 2005 |work=Metal Nightmare Webzine|title=Cirith Ungol Interview 2000 |accessdate=2012-11-04}}</ref>}}\n\n{{quotation|I remember some other possible band names we were considering: [[Minas Tirith]], [[Khazad Dum]], and [[Uruk-hai|Uruk Hai]], all names from \"The Lord Of The Rings\". Rob and I both liked J.R.R. Tolkien and Enzo Ferrari, so we knew our songs would cover both those subjects!|Greg Lindstrom<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ballbustermusic.com/hard_talk/08-2006/cirith_ungol.html |title=Hard Announcements: Cirith Ungol |website=BallBusterHardMusic.com |date=2006 |first=Jym |last=Harris |accessdate=2012-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710195742/http://www.ballbustermusic.com/hard_talk/08-2006/cirith_ungol.html |archivedate=2012-07-10 }}</ref>}}\n\n==Album cover art==\nEach studio album's cover art is taken from the cover of a [[DAW Books]] edition of a book in [[Michael Moorcock]]'s [[Elric of Melnibon\u00e9]] saga; the art is by [[Michael Whelan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metal-archives.com/bands/Cirith_Ungol/561 |website=Metal-archives.com|title=Cirith Ungol}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n===Current members===\n* Robert Garven - drums {{small|(1972\u20131992, 2016\u2013present)}}\n* Greg Lindstrom - guitars {{small|(1980\u20131982, 2016\u2013present)}}, bass guitar {{small|(1972\u20131980)}}\n* Tim Baker - lead vocals {{small|(1976\u20131992, 2016\u2013present)}}\n* Jim \"Jimmy\" Barraza - guitars {{small|(1988\u20131992, 2016\u2013present)}}\n* Jarvis Leatherby - bass guitar {{small|(2016\u2013present)}}\n\n===Former members===\n* Jerry Fogle - guitars {{small|(1972\u20131987; died 1998)}}\n* Neal Beattie - lead vocals {{small|(1972\u20131976)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metal-archives.com/bands/Cirith_Ungol/561 |title=Cirith Ungol - Encyclopaedia Metallum |publisher=The Metal Archives |date= |accessdate=2014-07-30}}</ref>\n* Michael \"Flint\" Vujea - bass guitar {{small|(1981\u20131987)}}\n* Bob Warrensburg - bass guitar {{small|(1987\u20131991)}}<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Interview |url=https://www.nocleansinging.com/2017/05/22/interview-cirith-ungol/|website=Nocleansinging.com}}</ref>\n* Vernon Green - bass guitar {{small|(1991\u20131992)}}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:100 bottom:80 top:0 right:10\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1972 till:{{#time: m/d/Y }}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\nScaleMajor = increment:5 start:1972\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1973\n\nColors =\n  id:vocals    value:red        legend:Lead_vocals\n  id:bvocals   value:pink       legend:Backing_vocals\n  id:lguitar   value:teal       legend:Lead_guitar\n  id:guitar    value:green      legend:Rhythm_guitar\n  id:bass      value:blue       legend:Bass\n  id:keyboard  value:purple     legend:Keyboards\n  id:drums     value:orange     legend:Drums\n  id:roadie    value:yellow     legend:Session/touring_member\n  id:lines1    value:black      legend:Studio_albums\n  id:lines2    value:gray(0.8)  legend:Other_releases\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Beattie     text:Neal Beattie\n  bar:Baker       text:Tim Baker\n  bar: