{"title_page": "Sammy Davis (ice hockey)", "text_new": "{{short description|American ice hockey forward}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|4|23|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pembroke, Massachusetts]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 163\n| weight_kg = \n| position = Forward\n| shoots = Left\n| team =  \n| league =  \n| played_for = [[Boston University]]\n| sex = f\n| ntl_team = USA\n| career_start = 2020\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Sammy Davis''' is an American [[ice hockey]] forward, who was drafted 1st overall by the [[Boston Pride]] in the [[2020 NWHL Draft]] and served as Boston University captain for three years.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/28/sports/boston-pride-select-bus-sammy-davis-first-overall-pick-2020-nwhl-draft/</ref>\n\n== Career == \n\nAs a high school athlete for [[Tabor Academy]], Davis was awarded the John Carlton Memorial Trophy, given out annually by the [[Boston Bruins]] of the [[NHL]].<ref>http://www.bu.edu/articles/2019/sammy-davis-triumphant-return-to-the-ice/</ref><ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/regionals/south/2013/08/24/pembroke-sammy-davis-has-high-goals-ice/OkBczgwQENvFIeFwKMYs2J/story.html</ref>\n\nDavis was named to the Hockey East All-Rookie team, scoring 26 points in 39 games in the 2015-16 season. She would put up 23 points in 35 games the next year, before missing the entire 2017-18 season after having bilateral labrum surgery on both hips.<ref>https://dailyfreepress.com/2018/12/06/missing-last-season-davis-captain-leader-womens-hockey/</ref> She finished her university career with 142 points in 147 games, being named to the Hockey East First-Team All-Star and MVP of the [[Beanpot (ice hockey)|2019 Beanpot Tournament]] in her final year.<ref>https://goterriers.com/sports/womens-ice-hockey/roster/sammy-davis/14216</ref><ref>https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/02/02/boston-university-lw-sammy-davis-set-to-defend-beanpot-title/</ref> She was recognised with the [[Sarah Devens Award]] in 2020, the first player from Boston University to win the award.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/nhl/pembroke-native-sammy-davis-receives-prestigious-college-hockey-award/ar-BB12DbkA</ref><ref>https://www.uscho.com/2020/04/14/boston-university-consummate-student-athlete-davis-named-2020-recipient-of-sarah-devens-award-postgraduate-scholarship/</ref> \n\nNear the end of her university career, she contacted both the NWHL and the [[PWHPA]] to explore her professional options, expressing a hope that the two organisations would merge. She would end up being drafted by the NWHL's Boston Pride in April 2020, after they traded for the 1st overall pick from the Toronto expansion team.<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2020/4/28/21239972/2020-nwhl-draft-boston-pride-select-sammy-davis-1st-overall</ref><ref>https://www.sportsnet.ca/olympics/women-hockey/boston-selects-sammy-davis-no-1-trading-nwhl-drafts-top-pick/</ref>\n\n=== International ===  \n\nDavis served as assistant captain for Team USA in the [[2018 IIHF World Women's U18 Championship]], where she scored 3 points in 5 games as the country won gold.<ref>https://teamusa.usahockey.com/page/show/2875700-samantha-davis</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==   \n\nDavis has a Master's Degree in Special Education, and has been admitted to the [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] doctorate program in occupational therapy.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/nhl/pembroke-s-sammy-davis-embraces-the-future-after-bu-hockey-career/ar-BB133pvY</ref> Her sister Alexandra played for [[Sacred Heart University]] from 2011 to 2015.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from [https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/368911/samantha-davis Elite Prospects]\n \n\n[[Category:Boston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston Pride players]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American ice hockey players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American ice hockey forward}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|4|23|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pembroke, Massachusetts]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 163\n| weight_kg = \n| position = Forward\n| shoots = Left\n| team =  \n| league =  \n| played_for = [[Boston University]]\n| sex = f\n| ntl_team = USA\n| career_start = 2020\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Sammy Davis''' is an American [[ice hockey]] forward, who was drafted 1st overall by the [[Boston Pride]] in the [[2020 NWHL Draft]] and served as Boston University captain for three years.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/28/sports/boston-pride-select-bus-sammy-davis-first-overall-pick-2020-nwhl-draft/</ref>\n\n== Career == \n\nAs a high school athlete for [[Tabor Academy]], Davis was awarded the John Carlton Memorial Trophy, given out annually by the [[Boston Bruins]] of the [[NHL]].<ref>http://www.bu.edu/articles/2019/sammy-davis-triumphant-return-to-the-ice/</ref><ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/regionals/south/2013/08/24/pembroke-sammy-davis-has-high-goals-ice/OkBczgwQENvFIeFwKMYs2J/story.html</ref>\n\nDavis was named to the Hockey East All-Rookie team, scoring 26 points in 39 games in the 2015-16 season. She would put up 23 points in 35 games the next year, before missing the entire 2017-18 season after having bilateral labrum surgery on both hips.<ref>https://dailyfreepress.com/2018/12/06/missing-last-season-davis-captain-leader-womens-hockey/</ref> She finished her university career with 142 points in 147 games, being named to the Hockey East First-Team All-Star and MVP of the [[2019 Beanpot Tournament]] in her final year.<ref>https://goterriers.com/sports/womens-ice-hockey/roster/sammy-davis/14216</ref><ref>https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/02/02/boston-university-lw-sammy-davis-set-to-defend-beanpot-title/</ref> She was recognised with the [[Sarah Devens Award]] in 2020, the first player from Boston University to win the award.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/nhl/pembroke-native-sammy-davis-receives-prestigious-college-hockey-award/ar-BB12DbkA</ref><ref>https://www.uscho.com/2020/04/14/boston-university-consummate-student-athlete-davis-named-2020-recipient-of-sarah-devens-award-postgraduate-scholarship/</ref> \n\nNear the end of her university career, she contacted both the NWHL and the [[PWHPA]] to explore her professional options, expressing a hope that the two organisations would merge. She would end up being drafted by the NWHL's Boston Pride in April 2020, after they traded for the 1st overall pick from the Toronto expansion team.<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2020/4/28/21239972/2020-nwhl-draft-boston-pride-select-sammy-davis-1st-overall</ref><ref>https://www.sportsnet.ca/olympics/women-hockey/boston-selects-sammy-davis-no-1-trading-nwhl-drafts-top-pick/</ref>\n\n=== International ===  \n\nDavis served as assistant captain for Team USA in the [[2018 IIHF U18 Women's World Championships]], where she scored 3 points in 5 games as the country won gold.<ref>https://teamusa.usahockey.com/page/show/2875700-samantha-davis</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==   \n\nDavis has a Master's Degree in Special Education, and has been admitted to the [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] doctorate program in occupational therapy.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/nhl/pembroke-s-sammy-davis-embraces-the-future-after-bu-hockey-career/ar-BB133pvY</ref> Her sister Alexandra played for [[Sacred Heart University]] from 2011 to 2015.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from [https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/368911/samantha-davis Elite Prospects]\n \n\n[[Category:Boston University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston Pride players]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American ice hockey players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "NHCLS", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sammy_Davis_(ice_hockey)"}
{"title_page": "Ferit Odman", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Ferit Odman\n| image               = Feritodman.png\n| image_size        = 250\n| landscape          = yes\n| caption             = Ferit Odman\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date         =  {{birth date and age|1982|7|7}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bursa]], Turkey\n| origin                = [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| genre               =  [[Jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| instrument       = Drums\n| years_active    = 2000&ndash;present\n| label                = Equinox\n| associated_acts =\n| website            = {{URL|www.feritodman.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Ferit Odman''' is a jazz drummer based in [[Istanbul]], Turkey.\n\n== Education ==\nOdman started his music studies in Sweden as an AFS exchange student in 1999, then received a full scholarship to Istanbul Bilgi University in 2001, where he obtained his B.A. in Music. In 2004, he attended workshops at the School for Improvisation in New York City. He was given a Fulbright Scholarship<ref name=turkful>{{cite web|last=Turkish Fulbright Commission|title=Facebook post|url=https://m.facebook.com/FulbrightTurkiye/posts/127917730604591|publisher=Turkish Fulbright Commission|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> to study at William Paterson University from 2006\u20132008.<ref>{{cite web|title=WP Magazine: Spotlight|url=http://www.wpunj.edu/news/wpmagazine/pdfs/wpmag_fall11_onlinesmall.pdf|publisher=William Patterson University|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> \n\n== Performing career ==\nOdman began his professional career in 2000 at the age of eighteen. He spent two years playing in New York City while pursuing his graduate degree, performing and recording with [[Brian Lynch (musician)|Brian Lynch]], [[Vincent Herring]], [[Peter Washington]], [[Benny Golson]], [[Jacky Terrasson]], [[Mike Moreno]], [[Sean Jones (trumpeter)|Sean Jones]], [[Ernie Watts]], [[Stefano di Battista]], Bertha Hope, [[Jim Rotondi]], [[Alan Broadbent]], [[Alex Sipiagin]], and [[David Berkman]]. Odman also played with a number of vocalists, including [[Sheila Jordan]], [[Kevin Mahogany]], [[Allan Harris]], [[Mark Murphy (singer)|Mark Murphy]], Deborah Davis, Ive Mendes, and [[Hilary Kole]]. He has played at many New York City clubs and festivals.\n\nSince returning to Istanbul, Odman has been a mainstay on the Turkish jazz scene, performing and recording with Kerem G\u00f6rsev and TRT (Turkish Radio Television) Big Band, among others. He was invited to a number of international festivals as a bandleader, including the [[North Sea Jazz Festival]], the [[Istanbul Jazz Festival]], the Prishtina Jazz Festival in Kosovo; the International Ankara Jazz Festival, and the Rabobank Amersfoort Jazz Festival in the Netherlands.\n\nOdman was featured in the May 2011 issue of ''Jazz Inside'' magazine.<ref name=Inside>{{cite web|title=Jazz Inside Magazine: May 2011|url=http://jazzinsidemagazine.com/publications/guide/may-2011-1|publisher=Jazz Inside|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Recording career ==\nIn 2010, he released ''Nommo'',<ref name=allmusicnommo>{{cite web|title=All Music Guide: Nommo|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/nommo-mw0002097183|publisher=AllMusic.com|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> featuring trumpeter [[Brian Lynch (musician)|Brian Lynch]], saxophonist [[Vincent Herring]], pianist [[Burak Bedikyan]] and bassist [[Peter Washington]]. In 2011, he released ''Autumn In New York'', featuring trumpeter [[Terell Stafford]], saxophonist [[Vincent Herring]], pianist Anthony Wonsey and bassist [[Peter Washington]].<ref name=aajautumn>{{cite web|last=Carey|first=William|title=All About Jazz review: Autumn In New York|url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=41160#.UkByp4YhA-Q|publisher=All About Jazz|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\nIn 2016, he released an all analog (AAA) Vinyl ''Dameronia With Strings'', which is a tribute to [[Tadd Dameron]] with six strings and featuring trumpeter [[Terell Stafford]], pianist [[Danny Grissett]] and bassist [[Peter Washington]].<ref name=allmusicdameronia>{{cite web|title=All Music Guide: Dameronia With Strings|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/dameronia-with-strings-mw0002913606|publisher=AllMusic.com|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> ''[[Down Beat|Down beat]]'' magazine gave four stars to ''Dameronia with Strings'',<ref name=Downbeat2>{{cite web|last=Potter|first=Jeff|title=Dameronia with Strings|url=http://www.downbeat.com/digitaledition/2016/DB1605/58-59.html|publisher=Downbeat Magazine|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> four stars to ''Autumn in New York'',<ref name=Downbeat>{{cite web|title=Downbeat Magazine (via Gretsch drums)|url=http://www.gretschdrums.com/?fa=artistdetail&id=1185|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=dbautumn>{{cite web|last=Micaleff|first=Ken|title=Autumn In New York|url=http://twitpic.com/95zjvb|publisher=Downbeat Magazine|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> and three and a half stars to ''Nommo''.<ref name=dbnommo>{{cite web|last=Brady|first=Shaun|title=Leading From Behind The Kit|url=http://twitpic.com/7aem8w|publisher=Downbeat Magazine|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors==\n* 2012 TCF (Turkish Cultural Foundation) Cultural Exchange Fellowship<ref name=tcf>{{cite web|title=Experiences and Observations of Fellows|url=http://www.turkishculturalfoundation.org/files/2012FellowsQuotes.pdf|publisher=Turkish Cultural Foundation|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>  \n* 2014 Rotary Professional Excellence Award (District 2440)\n\n== Discography ==\n=== As leader ===\n* ''Nommo'' (Equinox, 2010)\n* ''Autumn in New York''  (Equinox, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|title=Downbeat Magazine (via Gretsch Drums)|url=http://www.gretschdrums.com/?fa=artistdetail&id=1185|publisher=Gretsch Drums|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> \n* ''Dameronia with Strings'' (Equinox, 2015)\n* ''The Vinyl Collection'' (Equinox, 2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs |url=https://www.discogs.com/Ferit-Odman-The-Vinyl-Collection-Box-Set/release/10084764|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== As a sideman ===\n* [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]], ''\u0130htimaller'' (2016 Do\u011fulu Productions)<ref>\n{{cite web|title=Discogs|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/1991533-Ferit-Odman?filter_anv=0&type=Credits|publisher=Discogs.com |accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Fatih Erko\u00e7]], ''True Love'' (2016 Esen Elektronik)\n* Sinan Isik, ''Patience'' (2016)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev Trio & [[Ernie Watts]], ''Four Days'' (2015 Rec Jazz)\n* Bulut G\u00fclen, ''Su'' (2015 A.K. M\u00fczik)\n* [[Ozan Musluoglu]], ''My Best Friends Are Vocalists'' (2015 Sony Music Entertainment Turkey)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev Trio & [[Ernie Watts]], ''Emirgan'' (2014 Rec Jazz)\n* K\u0119stutis Vaiginis, ''Lights Of Darkness'' (2014 KV)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev & [[City of Prague Philharmonic Orchestra]], ''To Bill Evans'' (2013 Rec Jazz)\n* Asena Akan, ''Istanbul'un Izleri'' (2013 Kalan)\n* Ozan Musluoglu, ''My Best Friends Are Pianists'' (2012 Equinox Music & Entertainment)\n* \u00d6nder Focan, ''Songbook'' (2012 Equinox Music & Entertainment)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev & London [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], ''Therapy'' (2011 Rec Jazz)\n* [[Sezen Aksu]], ''\u00d6pt\u00fcm'' (2011 SN Music)\n* Uraz K\u0131vaner, ''Pieces'' (2011 Rec Jazz)\n* Ayhan Sicimo\u011flu, ''En Estambul'' (2011 IMM)\n* Joy Voeth, ''I Wish You Love'' (2010 JoyVoeth)\n* Jehan Barbur, ''Hayat'' (2010 ADA M\u00fczik)\n* Danielle Eva, ''Road and Moon'' (2010 Devour Music)\n* \u00dclkem \u00d6zsezen, ''Ghost\u2019s Note'' (2010 San Grafik)\n* Jef Giansily, ''Sketches'' (2009 Circle) \n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev, ''Diversion'' (2009 Rec Jazz) \n* Ozan Musluoglu, ''Coincidence'' (2009 Rec Jazz) \n* \u00d6nder Focan Group, ''Swing A La Turc'' (2007 Kalan Music) \n* SPIN, ''Ilk'' (2006 Aura Records) \n* Donovan Mixon, ''The Dance of Life'' (2004 DMC-Jazz)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.feritodman.com Official site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odman, Ferit}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:William Paterson University alumni]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Turkish jazz drummers]]\n[[Category:21st-century drummers]]\n[[Category:Turkish jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Ferit Odman\n| image               = Feritodman.png\n| image_size        = 250\n| landscape          = yes\n| caption             = Ferit Odman\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date         =  {{birth date and age|1982|7|7}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bursa]], Turkey\n| origin                = [[Istanbul]], Turkey\n| genre               =  [[Jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| instrument       = Drums\n| years_active    = 2000&ndash;present\n| label                = Equinox\n| associated_acts =\n| website            = {{URL|www.feritodman.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Ferit Odman''' is a jazz drummer based in [[Istanbul]], Turkey.\n\n== Education ==\nOdman started his music studies in Sweden as an AFS exchange student in 1999, then received a full scholarship to Istanbul Bilgi University in 2001, where he obtained his B.A. in Music. In 2004, he attended workshops at the School for Improvisation in New York City. He was given a Fulbright Scholarship<ref name=turkful>{{cite web|last=Turkish Fulbright Commission|title=Facebook post|url=https://m.facebook.com/FulbrightTurkiye/posts/127917730604591|publisher=Turkish Fulbright Commission|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> to study at William Paterson University from 2006\u20132008.<ref>{{cite web|title=WP Magazine: Spotlight|url=http://www.wpunj.edu/news/wpmagazine/pdfs/wpmag_fall11_onlinesmall.pdf|publisher=William Patterson University|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> \n\n== Performing career ==\nOdman began his professional career in 2000 at the age of eighteen. He spent two years playing in New York City while pursuing his graduate degree, performing and recording with [[Brian Lynch (musician)|Brian Lynch]], [[Vincent Herring]], [[Peter Washington]], [[Benny Golson]], [[Jacky Terrasson]], [[Mike Moreno]], [[Sean Jones (trumpeter)|Sean Jones]], [[Ernie Watts]], [[Stefano di Battista]], Bertha Hope, [[Jim Rotondi]], [[Alan Broadbent]], [[Alex Sipiagin]], and [[David Berkman]]. Odman also played with a number of vocalists, including [[Sheila Jordan]], [[Kevin Mahogany]], [[Allan Harris]], [[Mark Murphy (singer)|Mark Murphy]], Deborah Davis, Ive Mendes, and [[Hilary Kole]]. He has played at many New York City clubs and festivals.\n\nSince returning to Istanbul, Odman has been a mainstay on the Turkish jazz scene, performing and recording with Kerem G\u00f6rsev and TRT (Turkish Radio Television) Big Band, among others. He was invited to a number of international festivals as a bandleader, including the [[North Sea Jazz Festival]], the [[Istanbul Jazz Festival]], the Prishtina Jazz Festival in Kosovo; the International Ankara Jazz Festival, and the Rabobank Amersfoort Jazz Festival in the Netherlands.\n\nOdman was featured in the May 2011 issue of ''Jazz Inside'' magazine.<ref name=Inside>{{cite web|title=Jazz Inside Magazine: May 2011|url=http://jazzinsidemagazine.com/publications/guide/may-2011-1|publisher=Jazz Inside|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Recording career ==\nIn 2010, he released ''Nommo'',<ref name=allmusicnommo>{{cite web|title=All Music Guide: Nommo|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/nommo-mw0002097183|publisher=AllMusic.com|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> featuring trumpeter [[Brian Lynch (musician)|Brian Lynch]], saxophonist [[Vincent Herring]], pianist [[Burak Bedikyan]] and bassist [[Peter Washington]]. In 2011, he released ''Autumn In New York'', featuring trumpeter [[Terell Stafford]], saxophonist [[Vincent Herring]], pianist Anthony Wonsey and bassist [[Peter Washington]].<ref name=aajautumn>{{cite web|last=Carey|first=William|title=All About Jazz review: Autumn In New York|url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=41160#.UkByp4YhA-Q|publisher=All About Jazz|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\nIn 2016, he released an all analog (AAA) Vinyl ''Dameronia With Strings'', which is a tribute to [[Tadd Dameron]] with six strings and featuring trumpeter [[Terell Stafford]], pianist [[Danny Grissett]] and bassist [[Peter Washington]].<ref name=allmusicdameronia>{{cite web|title=All Music Guide: Dameronia With Strings|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/dameronia-with-strings-mw0002913606|publisher=AllMusic.com|accessdate=9 March 2016}}</ref> ''[[Down Beat|Down beat]]'' magazine gave four stars to ''Dameronia with Strings'',<ref name=Downbeat2>{{cite web|last=Potter|first=Jeff|title=Dameronia with Strings|url=http://www.downbeat.com/digitaledition/2016/DB1605/58-59.html|publisher=Downbeat Magazine|accessdate=6 April 2016}}</ref> four stars to ''Autumn in New York'',<ref name=Downbeat>{{cite web|title=Downbeat Magazine (via Gretsch drums)|url=http://www.gretschdrums.com/?fa=artistdetail&id=1185|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=dbautumn>{{cite web|last=Micaleff|first=Ken|title=Autumn In New York|url=http://twitpic.com/95zjvb|publisher=Downbeat Magazine|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> and three and a half stars to ''Nommo''.<ref name=dbnommo>{{cite web|last=Brady|first=Shaun|title=Leading From Behind The Kit|url=http://twitpic.com/7aem8w|publisher=Downbeat Magazine|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors==\n* 2012 TCF (Turkish Cultural Foundation) Cultural Exchange Fellowship<ref name=tcf>{{cite web|title=Experiences and Observations of Fellows|url=http://www.turkishculturalfoundation.org/files/2012FellowsQuotes.pdf|publisher=Turkish Cultural Foundation|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref>  \n* 2014 Rotary Professional Excellence Award (District 2440)\n\n== Discography ==\n=== As leader ===\n* ''Nommo'' (Equinox, 2010)\n* ''Autumn in New York''  (Equinox, 2011)<ref>{{cite web|title=Downbeat Magazine (via Gretsch Drums)|url=http://www.gretschdrums.com/?fa=artistdetail&id=1185|publisher=Gretsch Drums|accessdate=23 September 2013}}</ref> \n* ''Dameronia with Strings'' (Equinox, 2015)\n* ''The Vinyl Collection'' (Equinox, 2017)<ref>{{cite web|title=Discogs |url=https://www.discogs.com/Ferit-Odman-The-Vinyl-Collection-Box-Set/release/10084764|publisher=Discogs|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== As a sideman ===\n* [[Kenan Do\u011fulu]], ''\u0130htimaller'' (2016 Do\u011fulu Productions)<ref>\n{{cite web|title=Discogs|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/1991533-Ferit-Odman?filter_anv=0&type=Credits|publisher=Discogs.com |accessdate=10 June 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Fatih Erko\u00e7]], ''True Love'' (2016 Esen Elektronik)\n* Sinan Isik, ''Patience'' (2016)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev Trio & [[Ernie Watts]], ''Four Days'' (2015 Rec Jazz)\n* Bulut G\u00fclen, ''Su'' (2015 A.K. M\u00fczik)\n* [[Ozan Musluoglu]], ''My Best Friends Are Vocalists'' (2015 Sony Music Entertainment Turkey)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev Trio & [[Ernie Watts]], ''Emirgan'' (2014 Rec Jazz)\n* K\u0119stutis Vaiginis, ''Lights Of Darkness'' (2014 KV)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev & [[City of Prague Philharmonic Orchestra]], ''To Bill Evans'' (2013 Rec Jazz)\n* Asena Akan, ''Istanbul'un Izleri'' (2013 Kalan)\n* Ozan Musluoglu, ''My Best Friends Are Pianists'' (2012 Equinox Music & Entertainment)\n* \u00d6nder Focan, ''Songbook'' (2012 Equinox Music & Entertainment)\n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev & London [[Philharmonia Orchestra]], ''Therapy'' (2011 Rec Jazz)\n* [[Sezen Aksu]], ''\u00d6pt\u00fcm'' (2011 SN Music)\n* Uraz K\u0131vaner, ''Pieces'' (2011 Rec Jazz)\n* Ayhan Sicimo\u011flu, ''En Estambul'' (2011 IMM)\n* Joy Voeth, ''I Wish You Love'' (2010 JoyVoeth)\n* Jehan Barbur, ''Hayat'' (2010 ADA M\u00fczik)\n* Danielle Eva, ''Road and Moon'' (2010 Devour Music)\n* \u00dclkem \u00d6zsezen, ''Ghost\u2019s Note'' (2010 San Grafik)\n* Jef Giansily, ''Sketches'' (2009 Circle) \n* Kerem G\u00f6rsev, ''Diversion'' (2009 Rec Jazz) \n* Ozan Musluoglu, ''Coincidence'' (2009 Rec Jazz) \n* \u00d6nder Focan Group, ''Swing A La Turc'' (2007 Kalan Music) \n* SPIN, ''Ilk'' (2006 Aura Records) \n* Donovan Mixon, ''The Dance of Life'' (2004 DMC-Jazz)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.feritodman.com Official site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odman, Ferit}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:William Paterson University alumni]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:Turkish jazz drummers]]\n[[Category:21st-century drummers]]\n[[Category:Turkish Jazz Musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Kelpo11", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:a mistake", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferit_Odman"}
{"title_page": "Blaine Bishop", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image=\n|position=[[Safety (American football position)|Safety]]\n|number=23, 24\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1970|7|24}}\n|birth_place=[[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n|death_date=\n|height_ft = 5\n|height_in = 9\n|weight_lbs = 203\n|draftyear=1993\n|draftround=8\n|draftpick=214\n|high_school=[[Cathedral High School (Indianapolis)|Cathedral]]<br>([[Indianapolis, Indiana]])\n|college=[[Ball State University|Ball State]]\n|teams=\n* [[Tennessee Titans|Houston Oilers / Tennessee Oilers / Tennessee Titans]] ([[1993 NFL season|1993]]\u2013[[2001 NFL season|2001]])\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[2002 NFL season|2002]])\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=728\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue2=15.5\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue3=13\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=11\n|statlabel5=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue5=5\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n|statvalue6=1\n|nfl=BIS237924\n|pfr = B/BishBl00\n|highlights=\n* 4\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1996 Pro Bowl|1995]]\u2013[[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]], [[2001 Pro Bowl|2000]])\n* First Team All-Conference - Pro Football Weekly, UPI ([[1995 All-Pro Team|1995]])\n* Second Team All-Conference - UPI ([[1996 All-Pro Team|1996]])\n* Second Team [[All-Pro]] ([[2000 All-Pro Team|2000]])\n}}\n'''Blaine Elwood Bishop III''' (born July 24, 1970)<ref name=\"nfl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/blainebishop/2499657/profile|title=Blaine Bishop, SS|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> is a former professional [[American football]] [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] in the [[National Football League]] who played most notably for the [[Tennessee Titans]]. He was drafted by the [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]] in the [[1993 NFL Draft]].\n\n==Early life==\nBishop attended and played at [[Cathedral High School (Indianapolis)|Cathedral High School]] in Indianapolis - class of 1988<ref>{{cite journal |title=Irish Updates |journal=Cathedral High Lights |date=2009 |issue=Winter 2009 |page=48}}</ref>. He then attended St. Joseph's College and played football there before transferring to play [[college football]] at [[Ball State University]] in  Muncie, Indiana.  At Ball State University, Bishop earned All-Mid-American Conference Second-Team choice in 1992 as a senior and 1990 as a sophomore.  Named team captain his senior year.  Bishop made 243 total tackles, 13 pass breakups, 15 tackles for loss, 12 sacks, one interception, and one blocked kick.<ref>https://ballstatesports.com/hof.aspx?hof=14</ref>.\n\n\n==Professional career==\nBishop was [[NFL draft|drafted]] in the eighth round (214 overall) of the [[1993 NFL Draft]] by the [[Houston Oilers]]. Bishop went on to have a successful NFL career, earning [[Pro Bowl]] status four times in 1995, 1996, 1997, and 2000. He was also a three-time [[All-Pro]] selection, in 1995, 1996, and 2000. Bishop was widely recognized as the NFL's premier hitting safety during his tenure with the Oilers/Tennessee Titans. In 1999, the Titans made it to [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] in which Bishop started, however they lost to the [[Kurt Warner]]-led [[St. Louis Rams]]. In 2002, he replaced [[Damon Moore]] as the starting strong-side safety with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], forming a tandem with free safety [[Brian Dawkins]].\n\n==Personal life==\nShortly after retiring from his playing career, Bishop worked briefly at [[WTVF|WTVF \"NewsChannel 5\"]] in Nashville, Tennessee providing sports commentary, usually as part of Titans post-game coverage. He currently co-hosts a radio show in Nashville called \"Wake Up Zone\" on [[WGFX|WGFX \"104.5 the Zone\"]] from 6 AM to 10 AM central each weekday<ref>http://www.1045thezone.com/wakeupzone/</ref>. He also coaches the defense at Davidson Academy, a Nashville-area private high school. On Tennessee Titans game days, Bishop can be heard as part of the Titans Radio pre-game and post-game broadcast team on [[WGFX|WGFX \"104.5 the Zone\"]], affiliates of the Titans Radio Network, and at www.titansradio.com. He is represented by KMG Sports Management.  Bishop has also been an announcer for the Tennessee high school football state championship games along with former Titans teammate [[Kevin Dyson]].\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Football stats |nfl= 2499657 |cfl= |afl= |espn= 497 |cbs= 4699 |yahoo= 2581 |si= 2581 |pfr= B/BishBl00 |rotoworld= |dbf=BISHOBLA01}}\n\n{{Houston Oilers 1993 draft navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bishop, Blaine}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football safeties]]\n[[Category:Houston Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Ball State Cardinals football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image=\n|position=[[Safety (American football position)|Safety]]\n|number=23, 24\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1970|7|24}}\n|birth_place=[[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n|death_date=\n|height_ft = 5\n|height_in = 9\n|weight_lbs = 203\n|draftyear=1993\n|draftround=8\n|draftpick=214\n|high_school=[[Cathedral High School (Indianapolis)|Cathedral]]<br>([[Indianapolis, Indiana]])\n|college=[[Ball State University|Ball State]]\n|teams=\n* [[Tennessee Titans|Houston Oilers / Tennessee Oilers / Tennessee Titans]] ([[1993 NFL season|1993]]\u2013[[2001 NFL season|2001]])\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[2002 NFL season|2002]])\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=728\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n|statvalue2=15.5\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue3=13\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=11\n|statlabel5=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue5=5\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n|statvalue6=1\n|nfl=BIS237924\n|pfr = B/BishBl00\n|highlights=\n* 4\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1996 Pro Bowl|1995]]\u2013[[1998 Pro Bowl|1997]], [[2001 Pro Bowl|2000]])\n* First Team All-Conference - Pro Football Weekly, UPI ([[1995 All-Pro Team|1995]])\n* Second Team All-Conference - UPI ([[1996 All-Pro Team|1996]])\n* Second Team [[All-Pro]] ([[2000 All-Pro Team|2000]])\n}}\n'''Blaine Elwood Bishop III''' (born July 24, 1970)<ref name=\"nfl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/blainebishop/2499657/profile|title=Blaine Bishop, SS|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> is a former professional [[American football]] [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] in the [[National Football League]] who played most notably for the [[Tennessee Titans]]. He was drafted by the [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]] in the [[1993 NFL Draft]].\n\n==Early life==\nBishop attended and played at [[Cathedral High School (Indianapolis)|Cathedral High School]] in Indianapolis - class of 1988<ref>{{cite journal |title=Irish Updates |journal=Cathedral High Lights |date=2009 |issue=Winter 2009 |page=48}}</ref>. He then attended St. Joseph's College and played football there before transferring to play [[college football]] at [[Ball State University]] in  Muncie, Indiana.  At Ball State University, Bishop earned All-Mid-American Conference Second-Team choice in 1992 as a senior and 1990 as a sophomore.  Named team captain his senior year.  Bishop made 243 total tackles, 13 pass breakups, 15 tackles for loss, 12 sacks, one interception, and one blocked kick.<ref>https://ballstatesports.com/hof.aspx?hof=14</ref>.\n\n\n==Professional career==\nBishop was [[NFL draft|drafted]] in the eighth round (214 overall) of the [[1993 NFL Draft]] by the [[Houston Oilers]]. Bishop went on to have a successful NFL career, earning [[Pro Bowl]] status four times in 1995, 1996, 1997, and 2000. He was also a three-time [[All-Pro]] selection, in 1995, 1996, and 2000. Bishop was widely recognized as the NFL's premier hitting safety during his tenure with the Oilers/Tennessee Titans. In 1999, the Titans made it to [[Super Bowl XXXIV]] in which Bishop started, however they lost to the [[Kurt Warner]]-led [[St. Louis Rams]]. In 2002, he replaced [[Damon Moore]] as the starting strong-side safety with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]], forming a tandem with free safety [[Brian Dawkins]].\n\n==Personal life==\nShortly after retiring from his playing career, Bishop worked briefly at [[WTVF|WTVF \"NewsChannel 5\"]] in Nashville, Tennessee providing sports commentary, usually as part of Titans post-game coverage. He currently co-hosts a radio show in Nashville called \"Wake Up Zone\" on [[WGFX|WGFX \"104.5 the Zone\"]] from 6 AM to 10 AM central each weekday<ref>http://www.1045thezone.com/wakeupzone/</ref>. He also coaches the defense at Davidson Academy, a Nashville-area private high school. On Tennessee Titans game days, Bishop can be heard as part of the Titans Radio pre-game and post-game broadcast team on [[WGFX|WGFX \"104.5 the Zone\"]], affiliates of the Titans Radio Network, and at www.titansradio.com. He is represented by KMG Sports Management.  Bishop has also been an announcer for the Tennessee high school football state championship games along with former Titans teammate [[Kevin Dyson]].\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Footballstats |nfl= 2499657 |cfl= |afl= |espn= 497 |cbs= 4699 |yahoo= 2581 |si= 2581 |pfr= B/BishBl00 |rotoworld= |dbf=BISHOBLA01}}\n\n{{Houston Oilers 1993 draft navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bishop, Blaine}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football safeties]]\n[[Category:Houston Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Ball State Cardinals football players]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaine_Bishop"}
{"title_page": "NBA dress code", "text_new": "On October 17, 2005, [[National Basketball Association]] [[commissioner]] [[David Stern]] announced the implementation of a mandatory '''[[dress code]]''' for all NBA and [[NBA Development League]] players. This was especially noteworthy because the NBA became the first [[major professional sports league]] to implement such a rule, although [[National Hockey League]] rules state that a player is supposed to wear a jacket and tie to games and on charters if not told otherwise by the [[head coach]] or general manager.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott BurnsideNHLFollowArchive |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/columns/story?id=2198862 |title=Dress code suits NHLers just fine - NHL - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2005-10-20 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> The dress code went into effect at the start of the [[2005\u201306 NBA season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2194537 |title=NBA adopts 'business casual' dress code - NBA - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2005-10-18 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Details of the dress code==\nStern's dress code stated that all players must dress in business or conservative attire while arriving and departing during a scheduled game, on the bench while injured, and when conducting official NBA business (press interviews, [[Charitable organization|charity]] events, etc.). The new dress code banned fashions most often associated with [[hip-hop culture]], specifically: jerseys, [[jeans]], hats, [[do-rags]], T-shirts, large [[jewelry]], sneakers and [[caulk boots|timber boots]] (specifically, [[The Timberland Company|Timberland]]-type boots).<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2195141 |title=Stern sure players will comply with dress code - NBA - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2005-10-20 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n\nThis particular clothing is not allowed to be worn by players to interviews, games (on and off the bench), charity events, or any other occasion affiliated with the NBA and its developmental league (currently the [[NBA G League|G League]]).  Violators of the dress code are fined and may be suspended with repeat offenses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eskimo.com/~pbender/fines.html |title=NBA Fines and Suspensions |publisher=Eskimo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> The dress code was developed with the intention of combating image problems that have plagued the NBA in recent history.\n\nUnder current NBA dress regulations, if a player does not dress to participate in a game, he must dress in a manner suitable for a coach.  In the NBA, a suit or a [[sport coat]] is required for coaches,<ref name=ESPN /> as well as a [[necktie]].\n\n==Supporting arguments==\nThe league's image was in bad shape following the [[Pacers\u2013Pistons brawl]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=1927380 |title=Artest, Jackson charge Palace stands - NBA - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2004-11-21 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> Supporters also claim that most [[business]]es require their employees to adhere to a dress code of some kind so the NBA is not making any unusual demands. Moreover, the NBA was not requiring players to wear a suit and tie, as had been rumored initially. Further, many NBA teams already had dress codes, as dictated by coaches or general managers. Penalties for non-compliance usually involved fines such as having to pay for one's own airfare to wherever the team was going, rather than flying on the team charter.\n\n==Opposing arguments==\nCritics such as [[Allen Iverson]], [[Stephen Jackson]] and [[Paul Pierce]] claim that the dress code will not change a person's [[moral character|character]] regardless of what type of clothing they wear, and that associating hip-hop style of dress with [[crime]] or a bad image is [[Racism|racist]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2198089 | title=Richardson says dress code targets black players | publisher=[[ESPN]].com | work=[[Associated Press]] | date=October 19, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://seattletimes.com/html/sports/2002571873_nba20.html | title=NBA notebook: Dress code targets blacks, says Jackson | newspaper=[[Seattle Times]] | date=October 20, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014}}</ref> Iverson was also quoted to say, \"the dress code is not who I am and doesn't allow me to express myself.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/490598-allen-iverson-last-of-a-dying-breed | title=Allen Iverson: Last of a Dying Breed | website=[[Bleacher Report]] | date=October 13, 2010 | accessdate=February 1, 2014 | author=Sawyer, Jameel}}</ref>\n\nMany NBA and non-NBA sports figures also claim that it targets young black males and is a slap against [[hip-hop culture]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/22/AR2005102201386.html | title=Opinions on the NBA's Dress Code Are Far From Uniform | newspaper=[[Washington Post]] | date=October 23, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014 | author=Wise, Mike}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/writers/phil_taylor/10/12/taylor1012/index.html | title=Balancing act | publisher=[[SI.com]] | date=October 12, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014 | author=Taylor, Phil}}</ref> Most NBA players are sponsored by casual wear brands such as [[Nike Inc.|Nike]], [[Adidas]], [[Puma SE|Puma]] and [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]].\n\n==Impact==\n\nWriting for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Zack Graham said that although players were initially critical of the dress code, \"Over the years, NBA players accepted, then embraced and eventually began to have fun with the new dress code, changing men's fashion in the process.\"<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/features/david-sterns-nba-dress-code-legacy-w448591 | title = How David Stern's NBA Dress Code Changed Men's Fashion | date= 4 November 2016 | accessdate = 7 November 2016 | magazine = Rolling Stone | author = Zack Graham}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/610UC75Il?url=http://www.nba.com/home/index.html NBA Dress Code specifics at NBA.com]\n\n{{NBA}}\n\n[[Category:National Basketball Association controversies|Dress code]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association labor relations|Dress code]]\n[[Category:Clothing controversies]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Workwear]]\n[[Category:Casual wear]]\n\n[[it:National Basketball Association#Codice di abbigliamento]]\n", "text_old": "On October 17, 2005, [[National Basketball Association]] [[commissioner]] [[David Stern]] announced the implementation of a mandatory '''[[dress code]]''' for all NBA and [[NBA Development League]] players. This was especially noteworthy because the NBA became the first [[major professional sports league]] to implement such a rule, although [[National Hockey League]] rules state that a player is supposed to wear a jacket and tie to games and on charters if not told otherwise by the [[head coach]] or general manager.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott BurnsideNHLFollowArchive |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/columns/story?id=2198862 |title=Dress code suits NHLers just fine - NHL - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2005-10-20 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> The dress code went into effect at the start of the [[2005\u201306 NBA season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2194537 |title=NBA adopts 'business casual' dress code - NBA - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2005-10-18 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Details of the dress code==\nStern's dress code stated that all players must dress in business or conservative attire while arriving and departing during a scheduled game, on the bench while injured, and when conducting official NBA business (press interviews, [[Charitable organization|charity]] events, etc.). The new dress code banned fashions most often associated with [[hip-hop culture]], specifically: jerseys, [[jeans]], hats, [[do-rags]], T-shirts, large [[jewelry]], sneakers and [[timber boots]] (specifically, [[The Timberland Company|Timberland]]-type boots).<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2195141 |title=Stern sure players will comply with dress code - NBA - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2005-10-20 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref>\n\nThis particular clothing is not allowed to be worn by players to interviews, games (on and off the bench), charity events, or any other occasion affiliated with the NBA and its developmental league (currently the [[NBA G League|G League]]).  Violators of the dress code are fined and may be suspended with repeat offenses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eskimo.com/~pbender/fines.html |title=NBA Fines and Suspensions |publisher=Eskimo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> The dress code was developed with the intention of combating image problems that have plagued the NBA in recent history.\n\nUnder current NBA dress regulations, if a player does not dress to participate in a game, he must dress in a manner suitable for a coach.  In the NBA, a suit or a [[sport coat]] is required for coaches,<ref name=ESPN /> as well as a [[necktie]].\n\n==Supporting arguments==\nThe league's image was in bad shape following the [[Pacers\u2013Pistons brawl]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=1927380 |title=Artest, Jackson charge Palace stands - NBA - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=2004-11-21 |accessdate=2012-08-22}}</ref> Supporters also claim that most [[business]]es require their employees to adhere to a dress code of some kind so the NBA is not making any unusual demands. Moreover, the NBA was not requiring players to wear a suit and tie, as had been rumored initially. Further, many NBA teams already had dress codes, as dictated by coaches or general managers. Penalties for non-compliance usually involved fines such as having to pay for one's own airfare to wherever the team was going, rather than flying on the team charter.\n\n==Opposing arguments==\nCritics such as [[Allen Iverson]], [[Stephen Jackson]] and [[Paul Pierce]] claim that the dress code will not change a person's [[moral character|character]] regardless of what type of clothing they wear, and that associating hip-hop style of dress with [[crime]] or a bad image is [[Racism|racist]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2198089 | title=Richardson says dress code targets black players | publisher=[[ESPN]].com | work=[[Associated Press]] | date=October 19, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://seattletimes.com/html/sports/2002571873_nba20.html | title=NBA notebook: Dress code targets blacks, says Jackson | newspaper=[[Seattle Times]] | date=October 20, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014}}</ref> Iverson was also quoted to say, \"the dress code is not who I am and doesn't allow me to express myself.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/490598-allen-iverson-last-of-a-dying-breed | title=Allen Iverson: Last of a Dying Breed | website=[[Bleacher Report]] | date=October 13, 2010 | accessdate=February 1, 2014 | author=Sawyer, Jameel}}</ref>\n\nMany NBA and non-NBA sports figures also claim that it targets young black males and is a slap against [[hip-hop culture]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/22/AR2005102201386.html | title=Opinions on the NBA's Dress Code Are Far From Uniform | newspaper=[[Washington Post]] | date=October 23, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014 | author=Wise, Mike}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/writers/phil_taylor/10/12/taylor1012/index.html | title=Balancing act | publisher=[[SI.com]] | date=October 12, 2005 | accessdate=February 1, 2014 | author=Taylor, Phil}}</ref> Most NBA players are sponsored by casual wear brands such as [[Nike Inc.|Nike]], [[Adidas]], [[Puma SE|Puma]] and [[Converse (shoe company)|Converse]].\n\n==Impact==\n\nWriting for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Zack Graham said that although players were initially critical of the dress code, \"Over the years, NBA players accepted, then embraced and eventually began to have fun with the new dress code, changing men's fashion in the process.\"<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/features/david-sterns-nba-dress-code-legacy-w448591 | title = How David Stern's NBA Dress Code Changed Men's Fashion | date= 4 November 2016 | accessdate = 7 November 2016 | magazine = Rolling Stone | author = Zack Graham}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/610UC75Il?url=http://www.nba.com/home/index.html NBA Dress Code specifics at NBA.com]\n\n{{NBA}}\n\n[[Category:National Basketball Association controversies|Dress code]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association labor relations|Dress code]]\n[[Category:Clothing controversies]]\n[[Category:African-American-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Workwear]]\n[[Category:Casual wear]]\n\n[[it:National Basketball Association#Codice di abbigliamento]]\n", "name_user": "Mrschimpf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDetails of the dress code", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NBA_dress_code"}
{"title_page": "Stu Voigt", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image =  |\n   |birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1948|8|12}}\n   |birth_place = [[Madison, Wisconsin]]\n   |number      = 83\n   |height_ft   = 6\n   |height_in   = 1\n   |weight_lbs  = 223\n   |draftyear   = 1970\n   |draftround  = [[1970 NFL Draft#Round ten|10]]\n   |draftpick   = 259\n   |position    = [[Tight End]]\n   |high_school = [[Madison West High School|Madison (WI) West]]\n   |college     = [[1969 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]]\n   |teams       =\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|1970}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1980}})\n   | highlights  =\n* 3\u00d7 [[NFC Championship Game|NFC champions]] ([[1973 Minnesota Vikings season|1973]], [[1974 Minnesota Vikings season|1974]], [[1976 Minnesota Vikings season|1976]])\n   |nfl    = 2528002\n   |pfr    = V/VoigSt00\n   |HOF=}}\n'''Stuart Alan \"Stu\" Voigt''' (born August 12, 1948) is a former [[American football]] player. He played [[tight end]] for 11 seasons with the [[Minnesota Vikings]] of the [[National Football League]].\n\nBorn in the Westmorland district of [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]], [[Wisconsin]], he graduated from [[Madison West High School]] in 1966, where he was an all-state running back and track and field standout. His state record in [[shot put]] of {{height|ft=66|in=7}} in 1966 stood for 39 years<!--was not broken until 2005-->.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wisconsintrackandfield.com/news/2005/AOY.html | title= 2005 Athletes of the Year | work=Wisconsin High School Track and Field | accessdate = July 27, 2006}}</ref> He accepted a football scholarship to the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] and was a star halfback and tight end on some of the worst teams in [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Badger]] history, which won just three games in his three varsity years of [[1967 Wisconsin Badgers football team|1967]]\u2013[[1969 Wisconsin Badgers football team|1969]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nationalchamps.net/NCAA/database/wisconsin_database.htm | title=Wisconsin Football History Database | work=NationalChamps.net | accessdate=July 27, 2006}}</ref> all in his senior season.\n\nIn the [[1970 NFL Draft]], Voigt was selected in the [[1970 NFL Draft#Round ten|tenth round]] by the [[1970 Minnesota Vikings season|Vikings]] and played in three [[Super Bowl]]s {{nowrap|([[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]], [[Super Bowl IX|IX]], [[Super Bowl XI|XI]]),}} all losses. He retired after the [[1980 Minnesota Vikings season|1980]] season and was a [[color commentator]] on Vikings radio broadcasts from {{nowrap|1981\u20131990}} and {{nowrap|1997\u20132000.}}\n\n==After football==\nVoigt is the former Chairman of the Board of First Commercial Bank in [[Bloomington, Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.1stcommercialbank.com | title=1st Commercial Bank | access-date=July 27, 2006 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718065547/http://www.1stcommercialbank.com/ | archive-date=July 18, 2012 | df= }}</ref> In April 2006, he approved a loan increase and extension to Hennessy Financial, LLC owner Jeffrey Gardner, who personally owed him $4.5 million. Gardner failed to disclose the debt.<ref>https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-1-jeffrey-allen-gardner-2-stuart-alan-voigt</ref>\n\nVoigt faced charges in a [[Ponzi scheme]]: two counts of conspiracy to commit mail fraud; four counts of mail fraud; five counts of bank fraud; and seven counts of giving false statements on a loan application.  He also faced sixteen counts of making monetary transactions in criminally-derived property, two counts of making false statements to the FDIC .<ref>{{cite web | url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2015/04/15/fmr-viking-accused-of-multi-million-dollar-ponzi-scheme/ | title=Local Fmr. Viking Accused Of Multi-Million Dollar Ponzi Scheme | accessdate=May 15, 2015 |date=April 15, 2015 |website=CBS Minnesota}}</ref>\n\nA federal jury convicted Voigt on one count of bank fraud, and was ordered to pay a $100,000 fine by U.S. District Judge {{nowrap|Patrick Schiltz.<ref name=fogui>{{cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/ex-viking-stu-voigt-found-guilty-in-one-bank-fraud-count/367874771/|work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |last=Montemayor |first=Stephen |title=Ex-Viking Stu Voigt found guilty in one bank fraud count |date=February 6, 2016 |accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=sensimo>{{cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/ex-viking-stu-voigt-sentenced-to-six-months-in-prison-for-role-in-fraud-scheme/396973451/ |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |last=Serres |first=Chris |title=Ex-Viking Stu Voigt sentenced to six months in prison for role in fraud scheme |date=October 14, 2016 |accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=exvstuv>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17787142/former-minnesota-vikings-te-stu-voigt-gets-6-months-prison-fraud-scheme |work=ESPN |agency=Associated Press |title=Ex-Vikings TE Stu Voigt gets 6 months in prison in fraud scheme |date=October 13, 2016|accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref>}} He served a six-month sentence at [[Federal Prison Camp, Duluth]], and was released on May 26, 2017.<ref>https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/</ref><ref name=fvsvrel>{{cite news |url=https://www.twincities.com/2017/06/16/former-viking-stu-voigt-ready-to-pay-it-forward-after-release-from-prison/ |work=Twin Cities Pioneer Press |last=Sansavere |first=Bob |title=Former Viking Stu Voigt ready to 'pay it forward' after release from prison |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Football stats |nfl=2528002 |espn= |pfr=V/VoigSt00}}\n\n{{Vikings1970DraftPicks}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voigt, Stu}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:National Football League announcers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Madison, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Badgers football players]]\n\n\n{{tightend-1940s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|image =  |\n   |birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1948|8|12}}\n   |birth_place = [[Madison, Wisconsin]]\n   |number      = 83\n   |height_ft   = 6\n   |height_in   = 1\n   |weight_lbs  = 223\n   |draftyear   = 1970\n   |draftround  = [[1970 NFL Draft#Round ten|10]]\n   |draftpick   = 259\n   |position    = [[Tight End]]\n   |high_school = [[Madison West High School|Madison (WI) West]]\n   |college     = [[1969 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]]\n   |teams       =\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|1970}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1980}})\n   | highlights  =\n* 3\u00d7 [[NFC Championship Game|NFC champions]] ([[1973 Minnesota Vikings season|1973]], [[1974 Minnesota Vikings season|1974]], [[1976 Minnesota Vikings season|1976]])\n   |nfl    = 2528002\n   |pfr    = V/VoigSt00\n   |HOF=}}\n'''Stuart Alan \"Stu\" Voigt''' (born August 12, 1948) is a former [[American football]] player. He played [[tight end]] for 11 seasons with the [[Minnesota Vikings]] of the [[National Football League]].\n\nBorn in the Westmorland district of [[Madison, Wisconsin|Madison]], [[Wisconsin]], he graduated from [[Madison West High School]] in 1966, where he was an all-state running back and track and field standout. His state record in [[shot put]] of {{height|ft=66|in=7}} in 1966 stood for 39 years<!--was not broken until 2005-->.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wisconsintrackandfield.com/news/2005/AOY.html | title= 2005 Athletes of the Year | work=Wisconsin High School Track and Field | accessdate = July 27, 2006}}</ref> He accepted a football scholarship to the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] and was a star halfback and tight end on some of the worst teams in [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Badger]] history, which won just three games in his three varsity years of [[1967 Wisconsin Badgers football team|1967]]\u2013[[1969 Wisconsin Badgers football team|1969]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nationalchamps.net/NCAA/database/wisconsin_database.htm | title=Wisconsin Football History Database | work=NationalChamps.net | accessdate=July 27, 2006}}</ref> all in his senior season.\n\nIn the [[1970 NFL Draft]], Voigt was selected in the [[1970 NFL Draft#Round ten|tenth round]] by the [[1970 Minnesota Vikings season|Vikings]] and played in three [[Super Bowl]]s {{nowrap|([[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]], [[Super Bowl IX|IX]], [[Super Bowl XI|XI]]),}} all losses. He retired after the [[1980 Minnesota Vikings season|1980]] season and was a [[color commentator]] on Vikings radio broadcasts from {{nowrap|1981\u20131990}} and {{nowrap|1997\u20132000.}}\n\n==After football==\nVoigt is the former Chairman of the Board of First Commercial Bank in [[Bloomington, Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.1stcommercialbank.com | title=1st Commercial Bank | access-date=July 27, 2006 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120718065547/http://www.1stcommercialbank.com/ | archive-date=July 18, 2012 | df= }}</ref> In April 2006, he approved a loan increase and extension to Hennessy Financial, LLC owner Jeffrey Gardner, who personally owed him $4.5 million. Gardner failed to disclose the debt.<ref>https://casetext.com/case/united-states-v-1-jeffrey-allen-gardner-2-stuart-alan-voigt</ref>\n\nVoigt faced charges in a [[Ponzi scheme]]: two counts of conspiracy to commit mail fraud; four counts of mail fraud; five counts of bank fraud; and seven counts of giving false statements on a loan application.  He also faced sixteen counts of making monetary transactions in criminally-derived property, two counts of making false statements to the FDIC .<ref>{{cite web | url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2015/04/15/fmr-viking-accused-of-multi-million-dollar-ponzi-scheme/ | title=Local Fmr. Viking Accused Of Multi-Million Dollar Ponzi Scheme | accessdate=May 15, 2015 |date=April 15, 2015 |website=CBS Minnesota}}</ref>\n\nA federal jury convicted Voigt on one count of bank fraud, and was ordered to pay a $100,000 fine by U.S. District Judge {{nowrap|Patrick Schiltz.<ref name=fogui>{{cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/ex-viking-stu-voigt-found-guilty-in-one-bank-fraud-count/367874771/|work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |last=Montemayor |first=Stephen |title=Ex-Viking Stu Voigt found guilty in one bank fraud count |date=February 6, 2016 |accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=sensimo>{{cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/ex-viking-stu-voigt-sentenced-to-six-months-in-prison-for-role-in-fraud-scheme/396973451/ |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |last=Serres |first=Chris |title=Ex-Viking Stu Voigt sentenced to six months in prison for role in fraud scheme |date=October 14, 2016 |accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=exvstuv>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17787142/former-minnesota-vikings-te-stu-voigt-gets-6-months-prison-fraud-scheme |work=ESPN |agency=Associated Press |title=Ex-Vikings TE Stu Voigt gets 6 months in prison in fraud scheme |date=October 13, 2016|accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref>}} He served a six-month sentence at [[Federal Prison Camp, Duluth]], and was released on May 26, 2017.<ref>https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/</ref><ref name=fvsvrel>{{cite news |url=https://www.twincities.com/2017/06/16/former-viking-stu-voigt-ready-to-pay-it-forward-after-release-from-prison/ |work=Twin Cities Pioneer Press |last=Sansavere |first=Bob |title=Former Viking Stu Voigt ready to 'pay it forward' after release from prison |date=June 16, 2017 |accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Footballstats |nfl=2528002 |espn= |pfr=V/VoigSt00}}\n{{Vikings1970DraftPicks}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voigt, Stu}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football 